    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-12T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-12T18:00:00-05:00" n="423"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d423">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Commission/641: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Acting Chairman of the American Delegation to the General Disarmament
                        Conference (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_GHS1" type="to"
                            >Gibson</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-12T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 12, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>50. Your 62, December 12. For <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_DNH1"
                        >Davis</persName> and <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_WHR1"
                        >Wilson</persName>. <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_SH1">Saito</persName>’s
                    report of his conversation with <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CWR1"
                        >Castle</persName> is entirely misleading. The following is <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_CWR1">Castle</persName>’s memorandum of what was
                    said, written immediately after the talk: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Mr. <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_SH1">Saito</persName> asked me
                            whether we had yet received an invitation to participate in the work of
                            the League Committee of Nineteen. I said we had not yet been invited,
                            that we, of course, had had reports that such an invitation was
                            possible. I told him that we had reached no decision in the matter
                            because we should naturally have to see what the terms of reference
                            might be and whether such a committee would work solely under the
                            Covenant of the League of Nations. I said if the committee were one of
                            conciliation, as is reported, I saw no reason why we might not be
                            represented, but that we had not, as yet, reached any decision as to
                            what we would do.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
